<subSubSection lastPageId="38" lastPageNumber="39" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1436,998,2033]" lastBlockId="38.[151,1436,151,247]" lastPageId="38" lastPageNumber="39" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[203,339,1937,1962]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" reason="1">Comments.</emphasis>
Similar to the more abundant 
<taxonomicName box="[697,939,1938,1961]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="artemisiae">
<emphasis box="[697,939,1938,1961]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Liriomyza artemisiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[956,1141,1937,1961]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californiensis">
<emphasis box="[956,1141,1937,1961]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">L. californiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is relatively dark species with an infuscated orbit (not yellow, as stated in the original description) and first flagellomere, with the base of the flagellomere yellow. The phallus is more similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[826,957,2009,2033]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helianthi">
<emphasis box="[826,957,2009,2033]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">L. helianthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, in that the paraphallus is broad distally, and the distiphallus is narrow basally and expanded apically. The phallus is also nearly identical to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Spencer" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1974" box="[151,392,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="freidbergi">
<emphasis box="[151,291,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">L. freidbergi</emphasis>
Spencer
</taxonomicName>
, although this species has an entirely black antenna and is known only from 
<collectingCountry box="[1266,1328,188,212]" name="Israel" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Israel</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Spencer, K. A." pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="141 - 157" refId="ref92128" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1974) Some Agromyzidae (Diptera) from Israel. Israel Journal of Entomology, 9, 141 - 157." type="journal article" year="1974">Spencer 1974</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
